<dl id="un7030ae"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="un7" href="#un7030">UN7: </a>  <a href="../../FF/unbs/un7all.htm#un7030ae"> (V.A.2) 30(ae)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> continuity, <small>Blue</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="un7030ae"><li>Ulysses </li><li><a href="../../ulex/s/lexs.htm#un7030ae">2021</a> </li><li><a href="../../ulex/s/s86.htm#un7030ae">2017</a> </li><li><a href="../../ulex/s/s86.htm#un7030ae">1986 (17.1065)</a> </li><li><a href="../../ulex/s/l22s.htm#un7030ae">1922</a> </li><li><ms href="#un7030ae">MS PL-1</ms> </li><li>JJA 21:069 </li><li><a name="sd6" href="../udra/u17da.htm#sd6">Usage</a> </li><li><a href="../../ulex/s/sd6.htm#un7030ae">Draft: 17.6</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">The definitions of <mark>continuity</mark> which we have been considering, namely, those of Dedekind and Cantor, do not correspond very closely to the vague idea which is associated with the word in the mind of the man in the street or the philosopher. They conceive continuity rather as absence of separateness, the sort of general obliteration of distinctions which characterises a thick fog. <small> Bertrand Russell, <a name="BRIM" href="/udra/udex.htm#BRIM"><cite title="source">Introduction to Mathematical Philosophy</cite></a> (1919), 105</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
